s and decisions of migrant Filipino women in maintaining families and communities, raising questions about gender relations, the status of women in globalization, and the meanings of greater consumptive power that migration garners for women. The Force of Domesticity starkly illustrates how the operation of globalization enforces notions of women's domesticity and creates contradictory messages about women's place in society, simultaneously pushing women inside and outside the home.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aFilipino AmericansxSocial conditions. 0aForeign workers, Filipino. 0aWomen foreign workerszUnited States. 0aWomen household employeeszUnited States. 4aDocuments. 4aadversities. 4achildren. 4acultural. 4adomesticity. 4amaintain. 4amigrant. 4amigration. 4anegotiate. 4apolitical. 4apressures. 4asocial. 4athat. 4atheir. 4athese. 4aways. 4awell. 4awomen. 4awomens. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814768556423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814768556.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK